        {
            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "> Window-local options still have global and local values. Global values are for all buffers shown in the window, and local values are for only a single buffer. However, `vim.wo` changes both the global value and the local value, unless using double indexing, in which case it only changes the local value.\r\n\r\nAny chance this gets a documentation ? What double indexing\r\n\r\n```md\r\nvim.wo[{winid}]                                                                vim.wo\r\n    Get or set window-scoped options for the window with handle {winid}.\r\n    Like :set. If [{winid}] is omitted then the current window is used.\r\n    Invalid {winid} or key is an error.       \r\n```\r\n\r\n**So vim.wo.wrap is different than vim.wo[curwin].wrap ?**",
